art":null,"temperature":"","temperatureUnit":10,"unit":34}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":1200,"critical":[{"id":2,"title":"Centrifugation","icon":"CentrifugationIcon"},{"id":40,"title":"Overnight Step","icon":"Overnight"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1078349,"guid":"C59DF1E02AB211EB9732BB47823B20A1","previous_id":1078348,"previous_guid":"8DE655802AB211EB9732BB47823B20A1","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"E3EE3C3837D74FB4BC272914BEE55AE9","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"3.3 Molecular Assembly of GST Effector Proteins on Glutathione Beads"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"966787950A0E494EAF9C5785D95F84CF","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Wash the bead sets. For this, add <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> to each set and mix, centrifuge at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> to reduce the supernatants to 5\u00a0\u03bcL, resuspend the pellet, and dilute it in <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">, giving about <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">. The beads are ready for use and can be stored at <\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"CD9C26002AB211EB9732BB47823B20A1","order_id":2,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":50,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":"HPSMT"}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"D3B371B02AB211EB9732BB47823B20A1","order_id":3,"type_id":30,"title":"centrifuge","source":{"centrifuge":"3000","duration":120,"guid":"D3B371B02AB211EB9732BB47823B20A1","id":0,"label":"","pause":null,"preset":[],"start":null,"temperature":"","temperatureUnit":10,"unit":34}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"E747F4D02AB211EB9732BB47823B20A1","order_id":4,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":50,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":"HPSMT"}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"FB6D94602AB211EB9732BB47823B20A1","order_id":5,"type_id":25,"title":"concentration","source":{"concentration":8,"unit":"Nanomolar (nM)","title":"GST-effector"}},{"id":1054729,"guid":"ED7C17502AB211EB9732BB47823B20A1","order_id":6,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":4,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054730,"guid":"F4F27DD02AB211EB9732BB47823B20A1","order_id":7,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":0,"title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":1200,"critical":[{"id":2,"title":"Centrifugation","icon":"CentrifugationIcon"},{"id":40,"title":"Overnight Step","icon":"Overnight"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Small, monomeric guanine triphosphate hydrolases (GTPases) are ubiquitous cellular integrators of signaling. A signal activates the GTPase, which then binds to an effector molecule to relay a signal inside the cell. The GTPase effector trap flow cytometry assay (G-Trap) utilizes bead-based protein immobilization and dual-color flow cytometry to rapidly and quantitatively measure GTPase activity status in cell or tissue lysates. Beginning with commercial cytoplex bead sets that are color-coded with graded fluorescence intensities of a red (700\u00a0nm) wavelength, the bead sets are derivatized to display glutathione on the surface through a detailed protocol described here. A different glutathione-<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">S<\/span><span>-transferase-effector protein (GST-effector protein) can then be\u00a0attached to the surface of each set. For the assay, users can incubate bead sets individually or in a multiplex format with lysates for rapid, selective capture of active, GTP-bound GTPases from a single sample. After that, flow cytometry is used to identify the bead-borne\u00a0GTPase based on red bead intensity, and the amount of active GTPase per bead is detected using monoclonal antibodies conjugated to a green fluorophore or via labeled secondary antibodies. Three examples are provided to illustrate the efficacy of the effector-functionalized beads for measuring the activation of at least five GTPases in a single lysate from fewer than 50,000 cells.<\/span><\/div><br\/><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Section 3.3 'Molecular Assembly of GST Effector Proteins on Glutathione Beads' from 'Small-Volume Flow Cytometry-Based Multiplex Analysis of the Activity of Small GTPases' <\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/view\/small-volume-flow-cytometry-based-multiplex-analys-bpssmnee\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;\">https:\/\/www.protocols.io\/view\/small-volume-flow-cytometry-based-multiplex-analys-bpssmnee<\/span><\/a><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1630617662}